//Homescreen Investment Interaction Application
//Introduction In this experiment, there will be two stages through which you will progress. \n\nFirst, you will have to go through a series of statements and situations in which you will have to choose the answer that is most applicable to you. Afterwards, you will be presented with three different (fictional) investment opportunities. You should study those opportunities and decide how much (fictional) money you would like to invest in each of them. \n\nNOTE: It is not allowed to go back to previous screens during this experiment.
General Introduction
//ClassificationIntroduction Categorization Introduction You will be presented with 5 statements and 4 questions. Each of those statements and questions have 2 possible answers. Choose the answer that is most applicable to you.
//IntroductionInteraction Interaction Introduction The next part of the experiment will require you to make investments that you think are fitting for three (fictional) companies while considering different kinds of questions. \n\nIn total, the application will ask eight questions for each company. These will be distributed over 2 rounds with each consisting of four questions. \n\nThe investments that you make should be between $ 0 - 1000 with $0 being the lowest (o investment) and $1000 being the maximum. \n\nFor each fictional company, you will be asked four questions sequentially. \nAfter each question, you should make an investment after having considered this question in relation to the relevant company. You should also give a yes/no answer to each of the questions. \nThe money used for each new investment is independent of the other investments, the only requirement is that it is in the range of $0 - 1000. \n\nRemember that throughout this experiment, there is no "right" answer. Do what you think is best while making your decisions. \n\nNOTE: Remember that you are not allowed to go back to a previous screen. Also, you should not leave any field blank.
//Style Statements Statement 1 Statement 2 Statement 3 Statement 4 Statement 5 I act quickly in a chaotic situation in which it is unclear what the best action is that I can take. I consider myself to be relatively good at almost anything if I try my best. If something does not quite go the way that I envisioned it would go, it is more often due to external circumstances that are out of my control rather than my proficiency at that what I did. I prefer to do things in the way that I have always done it as that way works for me. I give preference to my way over alternative ways that I’m not familiar with even though, if mastered, those ways might be (but are not necessarily) more effective compared to my way. I would rather keep my $1,000,000 that I have worked very hard for to earn than to guaranteed lose the $1,000,000 and, in exchange, have an opportunity that has a very large potential to return $3,000,000.
//Style Questions Question 1 Question 2 Question 3 Question 4 You win $1000 and now have an opportunity to invest this money into potential Stocks that you think are almost sure to generate profit over this $1000. However, you might be wrong. What will you do? Today seems like a good day to you to make an investment. To you almost all stocks that you find interesting have the potential to, in your eyes, yield high returns today as you think that you see a lot of indications that this is the case. However, a while ago you decided to not invest in any new stocks for a while and stick with your, in your opinion, well-researched stocks no matter what happens. Now you think that this was a naïve decision and that the situation justifies a deviation from this decision. After all, the stocks that you had are not performing as good as you thought they would. So, you think that selling them and then re-investing the earned money might be better. What will you do? Due to some disturbance in the markets, almost all of the stocks that you have been watching have decreased in value quite a bit. You think that the stocks won’t go lower. This allows for some interesting investment opportunities. What will you do? You have item A which will probably give a small return on your investment and you can choose whether to keep A or switch to item B, C, D, E, F or G. You think that one of the other options is better and will yield a much higher return on investment, but you have no way of knowing if this is true or not. This means that you could be wrong. What will you do? Do not invest and keep the $1000 on a bank account Invest the $1000 into a high risk-high reward stock Do more research in the stocks that you find the most interesting and aim to make 1 good investment in one of these very interesting stocks while selling all of your old stocks Stick to the plan that you made a while ago and keep your old stocks, even though this might not be the best financial decision to make Make lots of smaller investments and short-term trades over most of the stocks that you find interesting with the aim to maximize your profits Decide to wait and not invest. After all, the stocks might go even lower and you don’t want to risk losing the invested money Keep A Take another item
