//StatusQuo Questions Question 1 Question 2 Question 3 Question 4
Do you have Faith in the main product of this company? Consider whether people will buy it. Remember: Just because you might think that this is a great or bad product, does not necessarily mean that others think the same way you do. They might or might not want this product. Think from the perspective of the general public and increase your investment if appropriate. What do other people think of this company? Will you let this influence your investment decision? Remember: Being open to analysis’s made by other people might aid in getting new perspectives on your investment. It might reveal interesting information that could give you the confidence needed to make a larger investment. What if this $1000 was all the money that you had to freely spent for an entire year. Would you be sure that you are comfortable with your current decision? Consider if you could handle the risk mentally. If so, it might be that you are too comfortable with your current decision. Consider increasing the investment amount. Stepping a bit out of your comfort zone might help you keeping more alert and more aware of relevant developments regarding your investment allowing you to respond quickly and prevent losses. Finally, are you convinced that this is the most rational decision that could be taken given the information that you currently have? Consider if the investment amount is appropriate relative to the available information. Also, consider if you truly came to this decision by thinking rationally and not emotionally. It might be better to increase your investment.
//Overconfidence Questions Do you have Faith in the main product of this company? Consider whether people will buy it. Remember: Just because you might think that this is a great or bad product, does not necessarily mean that others think the same way you do. They might or might not want this product. Think from the perspective of the general public and lower your investment if appropriate. What do other people think of this company? Will you let this influence your investment decision? Remember: It is probably not a good idea to make decisions based off of others analyses. However, considering their words with an open mind might lead to insights in risks that otherwise would have remain hidden allowing you to make investments that might be lower, but safer. What if this $1000 was all the money that you had to freely spent for an entire year. Would you be sure that you are comfortable with your current decision? Consider if you could handle the risk mentally. It might be wise to lower your amount such that you could reduce your risk. Finally, are you convinced that this is the most rational decision that could be taken given the information that you currently have? Consider if the investment amount is appropriate relative to the available information. Also, consider if you truly came to this decision by thinking rationally and not emotionally. It might be better to lower your investment.
